{"key":"processedPost-11661794","value":{"id":11661794,"first":11661187,"last":11662372,"when":1260990425,"utime":"12/16/09 09:07 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>NoOneKnowsHowToAct said:</b><br />I was told in another thread that grain doesn't fruit invitro.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Whomever said that should take a look at my gallery.<br /><br />If you prepare your rye grain properly, use weak coffee to hydrate the grains, and don't use them as spawn within a week of full colonization, you'll get invitro pins, provided you have a good fruiting strain.<br /><br />If the pins are forming early, it's an indication that the holes in your lids for gas exchange are too large, and the resultant loss of moisture from the grains is triggering pinning early as a survival mechanism.<br /><br />A few years ago, I did some experiments trying to deliberately grow fruits invitro.&nbsp; The grains were prepared with coffee and gypsum, an aggressive fruiting strain was used, the lids had 1/4\" holes instead of 1/8\" holes, and very bright light was applied from start to finish.<br />RR<br /><br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/06-03/747203393-Redboy_invitro_002a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/06-03/747203393-thumb_Redboy_invitro_002a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/05-10/056256190-grain_to_grain_invitro_2_004a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/05-10/056256190-thumb_grain_to_grain_invitro_2_004a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/03-52/233458486-invitro.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/03-52/233458486-thumb_invitro.